<dl id="n54135k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54135k">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54135k"> 135(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ suttee <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54135k"><li>FW 25.03 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54135k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54135k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54135k">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="ad8" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad8.htm#n54135k">Draft: I.1&sect;1.8</a>/2.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">It <font color="green">[the afterlife]</font> is now a life in which warriors feast with Odin in Valhalla on benches that are <font color="green">[108]</font> covered with corselets. A careful examination of Norwegian graves has proved fairly definitely the existence of the custom of &lsquo;<mark>suttee</mark>&rsquo; during the Viking period and the evidence of the Arab historian Ibn Fadhlan seems to show that the same custom prevailed among the Ru&ucirc;s. Horses, dogs, hawks and other animals were often buried with their masters, and the remains of such, burned or unburned, have frequently been found. <small> Allen Mawers, <a name="VIK2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#VIK2"><cite title="source">The Vikings</cite></a> (1913) 108-9</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Suttee: a Hindu window who immolates herself on her husband&apos;s pyre. </mm> </dd></dl>
